## The Numbers Behind April's Recalls

This year has seen a startling 314 food recalls so far, with 87 of them classified as Class I, the most severe. This is part of a growing trend that has seen a cumulative total of 672 recalls over time. Alarmingly, 66 instances involve repeat offenders, suggesting systemic issues within certain manufacturers.

## This Month's Highlights

This April, prominent cases included a Class I recall concerning supplements by Pure Vitamins and Natural Supplements, LLC, found to contain undeclared sildenafil, a prescription medication. These findings raise severe consumer safety concerns, highlighting the need for stricter controls in the supplement industry.

Another troubling trend is the mislabeling of allergens, with Zarlengo Italian Ice recalling multiple products due to undeclared soy. This oversight risks serious health implications for allergen-sensitive consumers.

## Repeat Offenders

Certain brands have continually failed to meet safety standards. For instance, Moonlight Packing Corporation tops the list of worst offenders with 11 recalls this year alone, all classified as Class I. Other brands such as Albertsons Companies LLC and Diva Fam Inc have similarly troubling records.

## The Verdict

While recalls are a necessary response to prevent harm, the frequency and severity of these incidents underline deep-rooted issues in food safety practices. Consumers are urged to stay informed about recalls and demand accountability from manufacturers and regulators alike.
